[1]
Date: Fri, 13 Feb 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Straits Times, 13 Feb 2004 [edited]
<http://straitstimes.asia1.com.sg/latest/story/0,4390,235071,00.html>

Leopard dies from bird flu in Thailand
--------------------------------------
A leopard has died from bird flu in a Thai zoo, a cabinet minister said on
Friday. The World Health Organization (WHO) said it had little information
about the case -- but if confirmed it could be the first known time the
disease has jumped to exotic animals or members of the cat family.
The clouded leopard died 27 Jan 2004 at Khao Khiew Zoo in Chonburi
province, 70 km south of Bangkok, minister of natural resources and the
environment Prapat Panyachatraksa said. "After double and triple tests,
veterinarians confirmed that the leopard died from bird flu," he told
reporters. But later in the day, Mr Prapat said authorities were still
waiting for the results of the 3rd test. He said the 1st one was done at a
state laboratory, while the 2nd was done at an independent lab. Both tests
showed the leopard had bird flu, but of different strains.
An official at the zoo, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
leopard's death "may have been as a result of eating chicken infected with
bird flu."
Bird flu has swept through Thailand, ravaging its poultry industry and
killing 5 people. The disease has struck 10 countries and territories in
Asia and has also killed 14 people in Viet Nam.
Clouded leopards are an endangered subspecies in South East Asia. WHO's
Bangkok spokesman, Mr John Rainford, said that even if bird flu has jumped
to leopards, any additional threat to human health would be minimal because
of limited contact between people and exotic cats.
A UN Food and Agriculture Organization official, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said he could not confirm the death of the leopard. But he
stressed that even if true, it was not clear whether the animal died from
the same deadly strain of bird flu that has been sweeping through Thailand
and other countries, or a milder strain that has been found in some parts
of Asia but is not known to have jumped to humans.
--
[This is an exceptional, unusual observation; confirmation or otherwise is
awaited. - Mod.AS]
