Date: Fri, 13 Feb 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Channel News Asia, Singapore, 13 Feb 2004 [edited]
<http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/southeastasia/view/70932/1/.html>

FAO says bird flu outbreak still not under control, urges vigilance
--------------------------------------------------
Asia's bird flu epidemic is still not under control despite a cull of more
than 80 million poultry, and affected nations must remain vigilant, the
UN's Food and Agriculture Organisation (FAO) said on Friday. "The spread of
the avian influenza virus in several Asian countries is still not under
control... Cambodia, China, Indonesia and Laos continue to report new
outbreaks in poultry," it said.
The UN agency said that cooperation with the regional nations hit by the
deadly virus had "significantly improved" but that the response to the
crisis in some poorer countries had been slow. "Countries realise that
cooperation and transparency are absolutely essential for the fight against
bird flu," the agency said. "While China, Indonesia, Thailand, and Viet Nam
have set up information and response structures, the situation remains very
difficult in some of the affected countries." The slow response to the
emergency was due to a lack of resources such as veterinary staff,
diagnostic tools, and transport, it said.
"In addition, the urgently required administrative and political structures
to run an effective emergency campaign are often not yet in place," it
said, adding that donor funds and emergency assistance should be better
targeted.
Veterinarians from more than 20 countries will meet in Bangkok from 26-28
Feb 2004 to discuss the economic impact of the bird flu crisis, strategies
to control the disease, and how to rebuild shattered poultry industries, it
said.
The FAO said that 80 million poultry in Thailand, Viet Nam, Indonesia, and
Pakistan had now been slaughtered in a bid to curb the spread of the
disease. It did not include more than 1.2 million chickens, ducks and geese
culled in China, where a total of 46 confirmed and suspected outbreaks of
the H5N1 virus have been reported, affecting 14 of the country's 31
provincial-level regions.
The deadly H5N1 strain of bird flu has emerged in Cambodia, China,
Indonesia, Japan, Laos, South Korea, Thailand, and Viet Nam. Pakistan and
Taiwan have announced weaker strains, as has the United States, where bird
flu has been found in the state of Delaware.
19 people have died in Viet Nam and Thailand but no other countries have
reported human infections.
